USD 466 Scott County Schools Custodian

Scott County Schools is looking for a reliable employee with an eye for detail. The ideal candidate will have experience in in the janitorial trades. The shifts we are looking to fill is evening from 3:00 PM to 11:00 PM.

Our employees must stand for long periods of time and be able to lift and carry janitorial equipment.

Applicant‚Äôs should be able to operate and maintain janitorial equipment including walk-behind and ride on scrubbers, floor buffers and both upright and backpack vacuums. When school is not in session this position will be expected to do maintenance work outside the facilities.

Position is Monday ‚Äì Friday with some weekend work.

Applications are available at our Administration Office located at 704 S. College Street. Scott City, KS 67871

post_text:
We received nearly 100 responses to our survey asking what your thoughts are about school for 20-21. Thank you to all who gave input! This input is helpful as we draft plans for August.

At this time we plan to start on August 20 as communicated this past spring when the 20-21 calendar was set. We continue to keep our attention on the local health situation, and will make accommodations as needed.

The district reopening plan will be communicated later in July. Guidance from the Kansas State Department of Education will be made available to us on July 10, and other state organizations who support schools will follow with guidance shortly after this date. Input from these organizations will be essential to our planning. Please contact the district office with questions, ideas, or concerns.

Until then, we hope our students, families, and community have an incredible Fourth of July weekend! Be safe and enjoy your family and friends!

Go Beavers!
#WeAreSC

The 2020 Census counts every person living in the United States and five U.S. territories. In mid-March, homes across the country began receiving invitations to complete the 2020 Census. Once the invitation arrives, you should respond for your home in one of three ways: online, by phone, or by mail. When you respond to the census, you'll tell the Census Bureau where you live as of April 1, 2020.
Responding to the census is not only your civic duty; it also affects the amount of funding your community receives, how your community plans for the future, and your representation in government.

Below is a link with more information...
https://usd466.socs.net/vnews/display.v/ART/5e84e9d86af14

post_text: This week is National School Bus Driver Appreciation Week. USD 466 would like to recognize our outstanding Transportation Department for their hard work and dedication to our district and students. They are responsible everyday for transporting many of our students to and from school. They face harsh weather conditions, traffic, and many other unexpected challenges all to make sure that our students get to where they need to safely. We can not express our gratitude enough for the lasting impact that each of our driver's have made in the lives of our students. Thank you again for helping to make Scott County Schools the best!! We would like to invite everyone to also express their appreciation to our Transportation Department for all that they do!!

post_text:
Three of these pictures are the new MS Vocal and Band rooms. We are extremely excited to be improving the environment our musicians work long, hard hours in to showcase their talents!

The aerial photo was taken by Lindsay Singley and Elizabeth Vulgamore. An overhead view sure shows the progress better than the view from the ground!

There will be a lot of concrete poured for the project in the next month. By the end of January, we should see some definite shape of the building. Work crews hope to get the walls up so they can begin working inside during the extreme cold of winter.

All parts of the project are on schedule and within our overall budget. It's hard to imagine that one year from now we will should be close to moving into all parts of these facility improvements!

People are always asking, "What is it that makes Scott County Schools so dang great?" And one of things we always tell them is that we have such great principals!

This group is extremely dedicated to the students and families we serve. They are willing to make the tough decisions and roll up their sleeves to get the hard work done. We appreciate the passion they bring to their job, the consideration for all students and staff, and the long hours they give to do it all!

Happy Principal Appreciation Month to Randy Huck, Shawn Roberts, Jana Irvin, and Brad McCormick!

Below is an important message from Scott County Schools, USD 466 District Nurse, Niki Depperschmidt.

"A letter was recently sent out by Hugoton Public Schools regarding meningitis. I‚Äôve talked to the health department regarding this matter. I was informed that the possible meningitis cases in Hugoton have NOT been positively confirmed as meningitis (neither viral or bacterial) by KDHE at this time. We will keep everyone informed of any updates but, as of right now there appears to be no threat of possible exposure to meningitis. Questions regarding this matter may also be directed to the Scott County Health Department."

You've probably noticed that we've had an ongoing saga with the yard on our elementary playground... Sprinkler issues and water pressure problems have plagued us, and it's hard to find time to let a playground recover when we need to use it for our kids.
Well, we think we have it resolved! New sprinkler heads have been installed and our crew is leveling the ground and planting seed this week. We will have to keep people off of it most of the rest of the summer, but think it should be in good shape for the beginning of the school year.
This crew in the picture has been incredible at resolving issues like this for the sake of our students. When you get a chance, let them know how great of a job they are doing!

Notice from the Scott County Schools,USD 466, District Nurse, Niki Depperschmidt:

The KDHE was notified of ONE student that was contagious with the Varicella virus(Chicken pox) at the Class 3A State Music Festival.

Students that participated in that event may have been exposed. The Scott County Health Department and the USD 466 Nurse have worked to verify that all USD 466 students and staff that attended have been fully vaccinated or a history of having had Varicella and therefore should have immunity to the virus.
However, parents should be aware of symptoms to look for in Varicella. See the attached flyer for information on Varicella. For further information, questions, or concerns you may contact the USD 466 Nurse at 872-7660, or the Scott County Health Department at 872-5774.

post_text:
An important message from our District Nurse, Niki Depperschmidt, RN:

We have recently been made aware of cases of Measles in Eastern Kansas. Currently NO cases have been reported in Western Kansas. There is no need to panic, but everyone should be informed of how measles is spread, the symptoms to look for, and prevention.

Please, take a minute and look at the attached information sheet from the CDC. The link below to the CDC can also provide you with more information:

https://www.cdc.gov/measles/index.html

You may also call the Scott County Health Department at 620-872-5774 for current statistics of measles cases in Kansas, to obtain the MMR vaccination, or for further information and education about measles and it's prevention.

You may also call me with further questions, or needs at 620-872-7660.

Thank you!

post_text: We are starting to see the first steps of the bond projects happen. It doesn't seem like much action, but we will see trucks like this testing the soil. We will also see lots of painted lines and flags out for surveying and marking utility lines.

post_text: The demolition of these houses has given us space for much needed parking. This should benefit students, staff, and visitors. The parking lot is covered with milled asphalt, and will likely settle for the next few months. Once ground has settled, we will pave it with a more long lasting surface.
